# **üìò STEP-BY-STEP GUIDE FOR SHAUNA**

### **Fixing the ‚ÄúNot all data was successfully written to the registry‚Äù error**

---

## ‚úÖ **Step 1 ‚Äî Copy the .reg file locally**

1. Go to the W:\apps\ODBC folder.
2. Copy this file to your computer:

   * **HT Live eMES_SQL_Registry32.reg**
3. Paste it into:

   ```
   C:\Temp\
   ```

---

## ‚úÖ **Step 2 ‚Äî Open the correct version of Registry Editor (32-bit)**

1. Press **Windows Key + R**
2. Type:

   ```
   C:\Windows\SysWOW64\regedit.exe
   ```
3. Press **Enter**
4. If prompted, click **Yes** to run as Administrator.

---

## ‚úÖ **Step 3 ‚Äî Give yourself permissions on the ODBC registry folder**

1. In regedit, navigate to:

   ```
   HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\WOW6432Node\ODBC\ODBC.INI
   ```

2. Right-click **ODBC.INI** ‚Üí **Permissions**

3. Click **Advanced**

4. At the top, click **Change** next to Owner

5. Type **Administrators** ‚Üí click **Check Names** ‚Üí click **OK**

6. Check the box:
   ‚úî *Replace owner on subcontainers and objects*

7. Click **Apply**

8. Go back to the Permissions window

9. Select **Administrators**

10. Check **Full Control**

11. Click **Apply ‚Üí OK**

---

## ‚úÖ **Step 4 ‚Äî Import the registry file**

1. In the same regedit window:

   * Click **File ‚Üí Import**
2. Browse to:

   ```
   C:\Temp\HT Live eMES_SQL_Registry32.reg
   ```
3. Click **Open**

You should **NOT** see any error now.

---

## ‚úÖ **Step 5 ‚Äî Close regedit**

Once imported successfully, close regedit.
Your ODBC settings are now installed.

---

If you want, I can also provide:
‚úî a version formatted as a **Word doc**
‚úî or a version written in a **checklist format** for her screen-share.
* **Timestamp** ‚Äì Date/Time (Optional)

This list acts as permanent storage and **will NOT be overwritten** when the MES Excel file refreshes.

---

## **STEP 2 ‚Äì CONNECT COMMENTS TABLE INTO POWER BI**

1. Open **Power BI Desktop**
2. Click **Get Data**
3. Choose **SharePoint Online List**
4. Connect to the new Comments list
5. Load the list into the data model
6. Go to **Model View**
7. Create a relationship:

```
MES Table.HU  ‚Üí  Comments.HU
Cardinality: One-to-Many
Cross Filter Direction: Single
```

---

## **STEP 3 ‚Äì ADD A POWER APPS WRITEBACK FORM**

1. Go to the **MES Inventory Velocity** report page.

2. Click **Insert ‚Üí Power Apps visual**.

3. Drag these fields into the Power Apps visual field well:

   * **HU**
   * **Material**
   * Any identifiers planners need for context

4. Select **Create New App**.

5. Power Apps will open and automatically generate a basic app.

Inside Power Apps:

6. Add a **Text Input** box ‚Üí name it:
   `CommentInput`

7. Add a **Button** ‚Üí label it **SAVE**

8. Set the **OnSelect** property of the SAVE button to:

```
Patch(
    Comments,
    Defaults(Comments),
    {
        HU: ThisItem.HU,
        Comment: CommentInput.Text,
        PlannerName: User().FullName,
        Timestamp: Now()
    }
)
```

9. Click **Save** and **Publish** in Power Apps.
10. Return to Power BI ‚Äì the embedded app will refresh automatically.

---

## **STEP 4 ‚Äì DISPLAY COMMENTS IN THE POWER BI TABLE**

1. Select the **main MES Inventory** table visual.
2. Add the field **Comments.Comment** to the table.
3. The comments will now appear next to the MES data for each HU.

---

## **STEP 5 ‚Äì REFRESH BEHAVIOR**

* The MES Excel file (on the network drive) **refreshes daily**.
* The SharePoint Comments table **remains untouched**.
* The HU ‚Üí HU relationship ensures comments always stay attached to correct rows.

---

## **STEP 6 ‚Äì VALIDATION CHECK**

Test with a single row:

1. Select a row in Power Apps.
2. Enter a comment.
3. Click **SAVE**.
4. Refresh Power BI.
5. Confirm the comment appears next to the HU and persists through refresh.

---

## **STEP 7 ‚Äì GO-LIVE CHECKLIST**

* SharePoint list created & accessible
* Comments table connected in Power BI
* HU relationship correctly set
* Power Apps writeback works
* Comments visible after refresh

---

